Launch

Beginning the grand tour of the outer solar system.

Jupiter Encounter

July 9, 1979 • 570,000 km closest approach
"Voyager 2 captured active volcanoes erupting on Io—the first discovered beyond Earth. It revealed Europa's cracked icy surface and discovered Jupiter's faint ring system."
— NASA JPL Mission Report

Saturn Encounter

August 26, 1981 • 101,000 km closest approach
"Voyager 2 revealed Saturn's rings to be far more complex than expected—thousands of ringlets with gaps and waves. It studied Titan's thick atmosphere and discovered new shepherd moons maintaining ring structure."
— NASA JPL Mission Report

Uranus Encounter

January 24, 1986 • 81,500 km closest approach
"The first and only spacecraft to visit Uranus. Voyager 2 discovered 10 new moons, 2 new rings, and found Miranda's bizarre fractured terrain with cliffs up to 20 km high."
— NASA JPL Mission Report

Neptune Encounter

August 25, 1989 • 4.5 billion kilometers from Earth
"The spacecraft came within 4,951 km of Neptune's cloud tops—the closest approach to any planet in the mission. It discovered the Great Dark Spot, supersonic winds, and active geysers on Triton."
— NASA JPL Mission Report

Pale Blue Dot

February 14, 1990 • 6 billion kilometers from Earth
"Look again at that dot. That's here. That's home. That's us. On it everyone you love, everyone you know, everyone you ever heard of, every human being who ever was, lived out their lives... on a mote of dust suspended in a sunbeam."
— Carl Sagan

Heliosheath Entry

August 30, 2007 • 84 AU from the Sun
⟐
"Voyager 2 crossed the termination shock—where the solar wind abruptly slows from supersonic to subsonic speeds. It entered the heliosheath, the turbulent outer layer of our Sun's influence."
— NASA JPL Mission Report

Interstellar Space

November 5, 2018 • 119 AU from the Sun
⟐
"Voyager 2 crossed the heliopause and became the second human-made object to enter interstellar space. Unlike Voyager 1, its plasma science instrument was still working—providing the first direct measurements of the interstellar medium's density and temperature."
— NASA JPL Mission Report
